During the coal gasification process at high temperatures ranging from 800 to 1300 °C and 30–70 bar pressures, coal is partially oxidised in oxygen or air atmosphere into synthesis gas, as shown in Eq. 5. The synthesis gas is typically composed of carbon monoxide and dioxide, hydrogen and unreacted methane, where the WGSR process (Eq. 3) enriches the syngas further to recover additional hydrogen. Thus, combining Eqs. 3 and 5 will lead to the overall reaction as in Eq. 6. Coal gasification is less efficient than steam methane reforming with 55%, although it has a larger single-train capacity.5C+H2O↔CO+H2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
